# ARTICLE 9: new-article-004 — Trump Before and After the Presidency
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
a9_figure = '<figure><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1541807084-5c52b6b3adef?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Donald Trump official portrait" /><figcaption>Donald Trump — 47th President of the United States. His two terms in office have been defined, in part, by the gap between campaign rhetoric promising accountability and a governing record that critics argue reinforced the very systems he promised to dismantle. Credit: The White House / Public Domain</figcaption></figure>'

a9_body = """
<h2>The Candidate and the Institution</h2>
<p>On June 16, 2015, Donald Trump descended a golden escalator in Trump Tower and declared his candidacy for the presidency with a speech that positioned him as a radical outsider to the corrupt political establishment. He would drain the swamp. He would lock up his political opponents. He would put America first. He was the only candidate with the personal resources and independence to take on the interests that had captured both parties.</p>
<p>The crowds that responded to this message did so with genuine conviction. Many of Trump's 2016 supporters were people who had watched the political system fail them — through deindustrialization, the 2008 financial crisis, a healthcare system that excluded them, a justice system they correctly perceived as operating differently for the powerful. Trump's outsider message was compelling precisely because it named a real problem. The question is what happened to those promises when they met the actual mechanics of governance — and what the record of two administrations reveals about the gap between campaign rhetoric and governing reality.</p>
<h2>Drain the Swamp: The Promise and the Record</h2>
<p>The "drain the swamp" rhetoric carried specific implications: fewer lobbyists in government, stronger ethics rules, an end to the revolving door between industry and the regulatory agencies that were supposed to oversee it. What the Trump administration delivered, according to analysis by nonpartisan watchdog organizations including Public Citizen, the Government Accountability Project, and the Revolving Door Project, was a record number of lobbyists and industry insiders appointed to federal positions — many to agencies specifically responsible for regulating their former employers.</p>
<ul>
<li>More than 180 former lobbyists were appointed to federal positions in Trump's first administration, according to a 2020 analysis by The New York Times and ProPublica — more than any administration in recent history had appointed in a comparable period</li>
<li>The Environmental Protection Agency was placed successively under Scott Pruitt, who had sued the EPA multiple times on behalf of energy industry clients as Oklahoma attorney general, and then Andrew Wheeler, a former coal industry lobbyist</li>
<li>The Department of Labor was led by Alexander Acosta — the former U.S. Attorney who had negotiated Jeffrey Epstein's 2008 non-prosecution agreement — until public pressure following the Miami Herald's reporting forced his resignation in July 2019</li>
<li>The Interior Department's Ryan Zinke resigned under multiple federal ethics investigations. His successor, David Bernhardt, was a former oil and gas industry lobbyist who recused himself from dozens of regulatory decisions involving his former clients but remained involved in shaping the agency's overall direction</li>
</ul>

<figure><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523995462485-3d171b5c8fa9?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="The White House" /><figcaption>The White House — where two Trump administrations pursued tax policies, regulatory rollbacks, and pardon decisions that critics argued served elite interests at the expense of the accountability rhetoric that powered his campaigns. Credit: Wikimedia Commons</figcaption></figure>

<h2>The Tax Legislation: Who It Actually Helped</h2>
<p>The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, the signature legislative achievement of Trump's first term, was presented as relief for working Americans. The Congressional Budget Office, the Tax Policy Center, and multiple independent economists analyzed the legislation's distributional effects with consistency: the law delivered its largest benefits in both percentage terms and absolute dollar amounts to corporations and high-income households.</p>
<p>The corporate tax rate was cut from 35% to 21% — a permanent change. Tax reductions for individual income were mostly structured to expire after 2025. According to the Tax Policy Center's analysis, a family earning $50,000 per year received an average cut of approximately $500. A household earning $500,000 received approximately $16,000. The wealthiest 0.1% of households received an average benefit exceeding $60,000 per year. These are not partisan estimates; they are the products of distributional analysis applied to the actual legislation.</p>
<p>The corporate repatriation provision — intended to bring offshore corporate cash back to America for domestic investment — generated stock buybacks at a record rate rather than the wage growth and capital investment that the bill's proponents had projected. The Federal Reserve Bank of New York documented in published research that the majority of repatriated funds went to shareholders rather than workers.</p>
<h2>Selective Accountability: The Pardons</h2>
<p>"Lock her up" — the rally chant directed at Hillary Clinton — implied a presidency committed to accountability for powerful political figures. What followed was a pattern of accountability that was strikingly and specifically selective. Trump issued presidential pardons to Paul Manafort, his former campaign chairman, convicted of fraud and conspiracy; Roger Stone, convicted of obstruction and witness tampering; Michael Flynn, who had pleaded guilty to lying to the FBI; and Steve Bannon, indicted for fraud in a private border wall fundraising scheme. These pardons were extended to men whose legal jeopardy arose from their service to Trump or their proximity to his network — not to the ordinary citizens whose cases Trump's anti-establishment rhetoric had ostensibly been directed toward.</p>
<p>Hillary Clinton was never charged with any crime. None of the "deep state" officials Trump repeatedly accused of criminality were prosecuted. The "lock her up" chant, as a governing agenda, produced no indictments and no convictions of any of the individuals it was directed at. It produced pardons for Trump's own allies.</p>
<h2>The Epstein Question Under Trump's Watch</h2>
<p>Perhaps nowhere is the gap between promise and record more acute than in the handling of the Epstein case. The populist rhetoric of accountability for the powerful — of equal justice — ran directly into the reality of Epstein's death in federal custody, under a Justice Department whose leader had personally intervened to declare, prematurely, that no foul play was involved. The cameras outside Epstein's cell failed simultaneously. The guards who falsified their logs were charged and then had those charges dropped. No one has been held accountable for what the DOJ's own Inspector General described as a cascade of institutional failures. The man who promised to drain the swamp presided over the most consequential unexplained in-custody death in recent American federal history — and the institutions of accountability functioned exactly as they always have for cases involving the powerful.</p>
<h2>What Two Terms Establish</h2>
<p>The record of two Trump administrations does not establish that Trump's campaign promises were cynical from the outset. It establishes that the structural forces that produce the outcomes he campaigned against — the revolving door, the two-tier justice system, the tax code tilted toward wealth — were not dismantled by his presidency. In some respects, they were reinforced by it. The question that history will ask is not whether Trump meant what he said in 2015. The question is why the system he promised to change remained, after eight years of his influence over it, substantially intact — and who benefited from that outcome.</p>
<div class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> Public Citizen and Revolving Door Project analysis of Trump administration appointments (2020); Congressional Budget Office and Tax Policy Center distributional analysis of TCJA (2017-2018); Federal Reserve Bank of New York working paper on repatriation and stock buybacks; reporting by The New York Times and ProPublica on cabinet appointments and conflicts; Department of Justice Inspector General report on Epstein death (2021); Trump pardon records; Miami Herald coverage of Acosta resignation (July 2019).</div>"""

a9_content = a9_figure + a9_body

