# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
a10_figure = '<figure><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1589829085413-56de8ae18c73?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="United States Capitol" /><figcaption>The civil legal system has been the primary venue for adjudicating sexual misconduct allegations against Donald Trump. Two federal jury verdicts in 2023 and 2024 found him liable for sexual abuse and defamation. Credit: Wikimedia Commons</figcaption></figure>'

a10_body = """
<h2>A Legal Record That Demands Examination</h2>
<p>This article reports on formal legal allegations made against Donald Trump in federal and state courts. Everything described below is drawn exclusively from court filings, sworn declarations, jury verdicts, and statements made on the legal record. Where allegations have not been proven in court, they are identified as allegations. Where courts have rendered verdicts, those verdicts are reported as established legal findings. Trump has denied all the allegations described in this article. His denials are on the public record. The existence of denials does not diminish the obligation of journalism to report the full legal record — including what juries have found.</p>
<h2>The E. Jean Carroll Verdicts: What a Jury Found</h2>
<p>E. Jean Carroll is a writer and advice columnist who alleged in published accounts that Donald Trump had sexually assaulted her in the dressing room of the Bergdorf Goodman department store on Fifth Avenue in New York City in the mid-1990s. Trump denied the assault publicly and repeatedly, denied knowing Carroll, and described her account as a fabrication. His denials — made publicly after his presidency ended, and thus not protected by presidential immunity — formed the basis of Carroll's defamation lawsuit.</p>
<p>In May 2023, following a nine-day trial in the Southern District of New York, a federal jury found Donald Trump <strong>liable for sexual abuse and defamation</strong> and awarded Carroll $5 million in damages. The jury's verdict was unambiguous: they found Carroll's account credible, Trump's denials false, and his public statements about her defamatory. The jury did not find rape under the narrow New York legal definition that requires vaginal penetration; it found "sexual abuse," which under New York law encompasses the forcible touching of intimate parts.</p>
<p>In January 2024, a second federal jury, in a separate defamation trial, awarded Carroll an additional $83.3 million after finding that Trump's continued post-trial public denials constituted ongoing defamation. Trump's attorneys immediately moved to reduce the damages; the central finding of liability was not disturbed.</p>
<p>These are not allegations. They are the findings of American citizens who heard evidence presented by both sides under the adversarial process, evaluated witness credibility, and reached conclusions under the civil standard of preponderance of the evidence. Two separate juries, in two separate proceedings, found Trump liable for sexual abuse and defamation in connection with the same underlying events.</p>

<figure><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1541807084-5c52b6b3adef?auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Donald Trump official portrait" /><figcaption>Donald Trump, found liable for sexual abuse and defamation in two separate federal jury verdicts in 2023 and 2024 in cases brought by writer E. Jean Carroll. Trump has appealed both verdicts. Credit: The White House / Public Domain</figcaption></figure>

<h2>The 2016 Federal Complaint: Jane Doe</h2>
<p>In April 2016, a lawsuit was filed in federal court by a plaintiff identified as Jane Doe, alleging that she had been trafficked by Jeffrey Epstein to Trump as a 13-year-old girl in 1994. The complaint alleged that she was recruited at Epstein's Manhattan residence with promises of modeling work, and that she was subjected to repeated unwanted sexual contact by Trump at parties at that residence over a period of several weeks. The complaint further alleged she was threatened and intimidated into silence.</p>
<p>The case was refiled in June 2016 in the Southern District of New York by attorney Cheney Mason, accompanied by a sworn declaration from the plaintiff and a sworn corroborating declaration from a witness identified as "Tiffany Doe," who described herself as a former Epstein employee who had recruited young women to his residence. In November 2016, days before the presidential election, the plaintiff voluntarily dismissed the case. Her then-attorney stated publicly that she had received death threats and was afraid to continue. No court ruled on the merits of the 2016 complaint. The factual allegations in the complaint were never tested in any evidentiary proceeding.</p>
<p>Trump's legal team denied all allegations and characterized the complaint as politically motivated. Those denials are on the record.</p>
<h2>The Pattern: Twenty-Six Accusers</h2>
<p>Carroll is the only accuser whose claims have been adjudicated by a jury. She is not the only woman to have made public accusations of sexual misconduct against Trump. As of the most recent comprehensive published accounts in 2023, at least 26 women have made public accusations. The accounts vary in their specifics — ranging from groping and unwanted kissing to rape — but share recurring structural features that have been noted by researchers who study patterns of sexual misconduct allegations.</p>
<p>The recurring features include: incidents concentrated in professional or social settings where Trump held power or prestige (the modeling world, beauty pageants, his professional office environment, social events); allegations of sudden, non-consensual physical contact without warning; subsequent pressure through NDAs, legal threats, or social and professional retaliation; and a social context — the world of New York business, celebrity, and elite entertainment that Trump inhabited from the 1970s onward — that overlaps significantly with the documented Epstein social network of the 1990s and early 2000s.</p>
<p>Prominent among the accusers beyond Carroll: Summer Zervos, a former contestant on <em>The Apprentice</em>, alleged Trump groped her in a hotel room in 2007 and filed a defamation suit in New York in 2017 when Trump denied her account. The case was ultimately resolved in 2022 after years of litigation over whether a sitting president could be subject to civil process. Kristin Anderson, a former model, told The Washington Post in October 2016 that Trump had groped her in a Manhattan nightclub in the early 1990s. Her account was corroborated by a witness who was present. Jessica Leeds told The New York Times in 2016 that Trump had groped her on an airplane in the late 1970s.</p>
<h2>The Standard of Accountability</h2>
<p>In a functioning democracy, the question of who holds public office is inseparable from the question of what that person has done and what they are credibly alleged to have done. The legal record described in this article is part of the public record of the United States. Jury verdicts are not opinions; they are findings of fact by citizens exercising one of the most fundamental duties of democratic society. Two such verdicts, in two separate proceedings, have found Trump liable for sexual abuse and defamation. The obligation of journalism is to ensure that this record is not suppressed, minimized, or forgotten — and that those in positions of public trust are held to a standard of accountability that their power would otherwise allow them to avoid.</p>
<div class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> Carroll v. Trump, SDNY (2023 liability verdict; 2024 damages verdict); Jane Doe v. Donald J. Trump and Jeffrey E. Epstein, SDNY case 1:16-cv-07673 (2016); sworn declarations filed in connection with the 2016 federal complaint; The New York Times comprehensive accounting of Trump accusers (October 2016 and updated 2023); The Washington Post reporting on Kristin Anderson (October 2016); Summer Zervos v. Trump, New York courts (2017-2022); reporting by The Atlantic and New York Magazine.</div>"""

a10_content = a10_figure + a10_body

